<dl id="n44146e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n44" href="#n44146e">N44 (VI.B.34)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n44all.htm#n44146e"> 146(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Quetzalcoatl</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Furthermore the early Mexicans were undoubtedly acquainted with Christianity&apos;s central truths. When Cortez and his six hundred landed there in 1519 they were amazed to find their arrival hailed as the fulfillment of a native tradition, strong as it was certainly old. They were told that, many centuries before, one who the natives called Quetzalcoatl&mdash;<i>the Precious</i>&mdash;<font color="green">[i.e., Brendan]</font> had come from some &ldquo;holy island&rdquo; of the northeast, in a boat with &ldquo;wings&rdquo; or sails. <small> F.J. Sheed, ed. <a name="FJSI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FJSI"><cite title="source">The Irish Way</cite></a> (May 1932) [<font size="-1">SAINT BRENDAN</font>&mdash;Navigator (483-577)] 38</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
